  "title": "Radical axis and centre",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Length of Common Tangent ",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Radical axis&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>The radical axis of two circles is the locus of a point, which moves so that the lengths of the tangents drawn from it to the two circles are equal.</p><p>Let the equations of the two circles be ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}\\text{x}+2{{\\text{f}}_{1}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}=0$ … (1)</p><p>And ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}\\text{x}+2{{\\text{f}}_{2}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{2}}=0$ … (2)</p><p>and let $\\text{P}\\left( \\alpha ,\\beta \\right)$ be any point such that the tangents from it to these circles are equal.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"461\" height=\"153\"></p><p>Now $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }PA=\\sqrt{{{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{\\beta }^{2}}+2{{g}_{1}}\\alpha +2{{f}_{1}}\\beta +{{c}_{1}}}$</p><p>and $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ PB}=\\sqrt{{{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{\\beta }^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}\\alpha +2{{\\text{f}}_{2}}\\beta +{{\\text{c}}_{2}}}$</p><p>We have $\\text{PA}=\\text{PB }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ P}{{\\text{A}}^{2}}=\\text{P}{{\\text{B}}^{2}}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{\\beta }^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}\\alpha +2{{\\text{f}}_{1}}\\beta +{{\\text{c}}_{1}}={{\\alpha }^{2}}+{{\\beta }^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}\\alpha +2{{\\text{f}}_{2}}\\beta +{{\\text{c}}_{2}}$</p><p>or $2\\left( {{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}} \\right)\\alpha +2\\left( {{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}} \\right)\\beta +{{c}_{1}}-{{c}_{2}}=0$</p><p>Hence, the locus of $P\\left( \\alpha ,\\beta \\right)$ is $2\\left( {{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}} \\right)x+2\\left( {{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}} \\right)y+{{c}_{1}}-{{c}_{2}}=0$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ The equation of the radical axis of circles (1) and (2) is</p><p>$2\\left( {{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}} \\right)x+2\\left( {{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}} \\right)y+{{c}_{1}}-{{c}_{2}}=0$</p><p><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(i) If we denote the L.H.S. of (1) and (2) by ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}$ and ${{\\text{S}}_{2}}$ respectively, we see that the equation of the radical axis of the circles ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}=0$ and ${{\\text{S}}_{2}}=0$ will be ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}-{{\\text{S}}_{2}}=0$</p><p>Hence in order to write down the equation of the radical axis of two circles make the coefficient of ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}$ in the equation of the two circles unity and then subtract.</p><p>(ii) Since ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}-{{\\text{S}}_{2}}$ is of the form ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}+\\text{k}{{\\text{S}}_{2}}=0$, where $\\text{k}=-1$ hence radical axis of two circles will pass through the point of intersection of the two circles if they cut each other. Thus</p><ol><li>if the two circles cut each other at two different points, then their radical axis will be their common chord.</li><li>if the two circles touch each other (internally or externally), then their radical axis will be the common tangent at the point of contact.</li><li>According to the above definition radical axis of two intersecting circles will be their common chord but from any point on this chord lying inside the circles no tangent can be drawn to the circles and hence definition of radical axis as given above is not correct and must be modified.</li></ol><p>Modified definition of radical axis:</p><p>If ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}=0$ and ${{\\text{S}}_{2}}=0$ be the equations of the two circles where coefficients of ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}$ in ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}$ and ${{\\text{S}}_{2}}$ are equal, then their radical axis is the straight line ${{\\text{S}}_{1}}-{{\\text{S}}_{2}}=0$.</p>",
      "position": 0,
