      "title": "Properties of radical axis",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Properties of Radical axis</strong></h3><p><strong>Property I : The radical axis of two circles is perpendicular to the line of Centre’s.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let the equation of the two circles be</p><p>${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2{{g}_{1}}x+2{{f}_{1}}y+{{c}_{1}}=0$ … (1)</p><p>and ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2{{g}_{2}}x+2{{f}_{2}}y+{{c}_{2}}=0$ … (2)</p><p>Let $A$ and $B$ be the Centre’s of the two circles (1) and (2) respectively, then</p><p>$A\\equiv \\left( -{{g}_{1}},-{{f}_{1}} \\right)\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }B\\equiv \\left( -{{g}_{2}},-{{f}_{2}} \\right)$</p><p>slope of $\\text{AB}=\\frac{{{\\text{f}}_{2}}-{{\\text{f}}_{1}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}-{{\\text{g}}_{1}}}={{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (say) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$</p><p>$\\begin{matrix} {} \\\\ 2\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}-{{\\text{g}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{x}+2\\left( {{\\text{f}}_{1}}-{{\\text{f}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}-{{\\text{c}}_{2}}=0 &nbsp;… (3) \\\\ \\end{matrix}$</p><p>Its $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ slope $=\\frac{{{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}}}{{{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}}}=-\\frac{{{g}_{2}}-{{g}_{1}}}{{{f}_{2}}-{{f}_{1}}}={{m}_{2}}$ (say)</p><p>since ${{m}_{1}}{{m}_{2}}=-1$, hence radical axis is perpendicular to the line joining the Centre’s.</p><p><strong>Property II </strong>: The radical axis of three circles taken two at a time are concurrent. Let the equation of the three circles be</p><p>${{\\text{S}}_{1}}\\equiv {{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}\\text{x}+2{{\\text{f}}_{1}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}=0$ … (1)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{S}}_{2}}\\equiv {{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}\\text{x}+2{{\\text{f}}_{2}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{2}}=0$ … (2)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{S}}_{3}}\\equiv {{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}+2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{3}}\\text{x}+2{{\\text{f}}_{3}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{3}}=0$ … (3)</p><p>Radical axis of circles (1) and (2), (2) and (3) and (3) and (1) are</p><p>${{\\text{S}}_{1}}-{{\\text{S}}_{2}}\\equiv =2\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}-{{\\text{g}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{x}+2\\left( {{\\text{f}}_{1}}-{{\\text{f}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}-{{\\text{c}}_{2}}=0$ … (4)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{S}}_{2}}-{{\\text{S}}_{3}}\\equiv 2\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{2}}-{{\\text{g}}_{3}} \\right)\\text{x}+2\\left( {{\\text{f}}_{2}}-{{\\text{f}}_{3}} \\right)\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{2}}-{{\\text{c}}_{3}}=0$ … (5)</p><p>and ${{\\text{S}}_{3}}-{{\\text{S}}_{1}}\\equiv =2\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{3}}-{{\\text{g}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{x}+2\\left( {{\\text{f}}_{3}}-{{\\text{f}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{3}}-{{\\text{c}}_{1}}=0$ … (6)</p><p>Adding (4), (5) and (6) we see that L.H.S. is indentically zero, hence the three lines are concurrent.</p><p><strong>Note </strong>: The point of intersection of these three radical axes is called the radical centre of the three circles.</p><p><strong>Property III: The radical axis of two circles bisects their common tangent.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $\\text{AB}$ be one of the common tangents meeting the radical axis at $\\text{P}$, then since $\\text{P}$ lies on the radical axis hence by definition of radical axis $\\text{PA}=\\text{PB}$.</p><p>Thus, the radical axis bisects the common chord.</p><p><strong>Property IV: If two circles cut a third circle orthogonally, then the radical axis of the two circles will pass through the centre of the third circle.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Or&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>The locus of the centre of a circle cutting two given circles orthogonally is the radical axis of the two circles.&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let the circle ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2gx+2fy+c=0$ … (1)</p><p>cut the circles</p><p>${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2{{g}_{1}}x+2{{f}_{1}}y+{{c}_{1}}=0$ … (2)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2{{g}_{2}}x+2{{f}_{2}}y+{{c}_{2}}=0$ … (3)</p><p>orthogonally, then</p><p>$2\\text{g}{{\\text{g}}_{1}}+2\\text{f}{{\\text{f}}_{1}}=\\text{c}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}}\\ldots \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (4) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ and }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }2\\text{g}{{\\text{g}}_{2}}+2\\text{f}{{\\text{f}}_{2}}=\\text{c}+{{\\text{c}}_{2}}$ … (5)</p><p>$~\\left( 4 \\right)-\\left( 5 \\right)\\text{, }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ we }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ get }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }2\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{g}}_{1}}-{{\\text{g}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{g}+2\\left( {{\\text{f}}_{1}}-{{\\text{f}}_{2}} \\right)\\text{f}={{\\text{c}}_{1}}-{{\\text{c}}_{2}}$ … (6)</p><p>centre of circle (1) is $\\left( -g,-f \\right)$. $\\therefore $ from (6) locus of $\\left( -g,-f \\right)$ is</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} {} &amp; 2\\left( {{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}} \\right)\\left( -x \\right)+2\\left( {{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}} \\right)\\left( -y \\right)={{c}_{1}}-{{c}_{2}} \\\\ \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ or }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } &amp; 2\\left( {{g}_{1}}-{{g}_{2}} \\right)x+2\\left( {{f}_{1}}-{{f}_{2}} \\right)y+{{c}_{1}}-{{c}_{2}}=0 &nbsp;… (7) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Clearly (7) is the radical axis of circles (2) and (3).</p>",
      "position": 1,
